  <body>
    <h3>UPPER LIMB &amp; NECK EXAMINATION (Whiplash Injury Scenario)</h3>
    <div class="video-container"> <iframe src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/p4GHGCM_aiM"

        title="Comprehensive Upper Limb &amp; Neck Examination Guide | PLAB2/UKMLA"

        allow="accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture; web-share"

        referrerpolicy="strict-origin-when-cross-origin" allowfullscreen="" frameborder="0"></iframe>
    </div>
    <p><em>Scenario: Patient (Samra, 23) presented after RTA (hit from behind at
        traffic signal) with neck pain that started a few hours after the
        accident. Task: Talk to patient, assess, discuss management.</em></p>
    <h4>I. HISTORY TAKING (Key Points from Transcript)</h4>
    <ol>
      <li><strong>Presenting Complaint:</strong> Neck Pain
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Socrates for Pain:</strong>
            <ul>
              <li><strong>S</strong>ite: Neck area (patient may point).</li>
              <li><strong>O</strong>nset: A few hours *after* the RTA
                (suggestive of whiplash rather than immediate fracture).</li>
              <li><strong>C</strong>haracter: Dull pain.</li>
              <li><strong>R</strong>adiation: Patient reports no radiation.</li>
              <li><strong>A</strong>ssociated Symptoms: Possible neck stiffness.</li>
              <li><strong>T</strong>iming: Started this morning after last
                night's accident.</li>
              <li><strong>E</strong>xacerbating/Relieving: (To be explored)</li>
              <li><strong>S</strong>everity: e.g., 5/10.</li>
            </ul>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li><strong>Mechanism of Injury:</strong>
        <ul>
          <li>Car stationary at traffic signal, hit from the back. (<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=p4GHGCM_aiM&amp;t=152s"

              class="timestamp">2:32</a>)</li>
          <li>Leads to typical whiplash movement (forward then backward). (<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=p4GHGCM_aiM&amp;t=183s"

              class="timestamp">3:03</a>)</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li><strong>Initial Instruction to Patient:</strong>
        <ul>
          <li>"Please <strong>don't move your head and neck</strong> until
            we've assessed further." (<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=p4GHGCM_aiM&amp;t=224s"

              class="timestamp">3:44</a>) <em>(Crucial if cervical fracture not
              yet ruled out).</em></li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li><strong>Other RTA Related Questions:</strong>
        <ul>
          <li>Any other trauma or injuries from the accident? (<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=p4GHGCM_aiM&amp;t=283s"

              class="timestamp">4:43</a>)</li>
          <li>Nausea, vomiting? (<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=p4GHGCM_aiM&amp;t=287s"

              class="timestamp">4:47</a>)</li>
          <li>Headache? (<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=p4GHGCM_aiM&amp;t=289s"

              class="timestamp">4:49</a>)</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li><strong>Upper Limb Neurological Screening Questions (History):</strong>
        <ul>
          <li>Any numbness or tingling in the arms/upper limbs? (<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=p4GHGCM_aiM&amp;t=301s"

              class="timestamp">5:01</a>) - Patient says No.</li>
          <li>Any problems with power in the arms? Able to lift things properly?
            (<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=p4GHGCM_aiM&amp;t=309s" class="timestamp">5:09</a>)
            - Patient says Yes, able.</li>
          <li><em>(Rationale: If history is negative, full Upper Limb Neuro exam
              might be expedited or focused if time is short).</em></li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li><strong>Past Medical History:</strong>
        <ul>
          <li>Any previous neck problems?</li>
          <li>Any previous surgeries (especially neck/spine)? (<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=p4GHGCM_aiM&amp;t=362s"

              class="timestamp">6:02</a>)</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li><strong>Lifestyle History:</strong>
        <ul>
          <li>Smoking, alcohol, diet, physical activity - <em>Generally skip in
              this acute trauma scenario to save time.</em> (<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=p4GHGCM_aiM&amp;t=372s"

              class="timestamp">6:12</a>)</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
    </ol>
   
        
        
        
        




    <li><strong>Upper Limb Examination:</strong> (<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=p4GHGCM_aiM&amp;t=472s"

        class="timestamp">7:52</a>)
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Inspection:</strong> Quickly from front and back (scars,
          swelling, wasting, asymmetry). (<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=p4GHGCM_aiM&amp;t=483s"

            class="timestamp">8:03</a>)</li>
        <li><strong>Palpation:</strong> Temperature, tenderness, pulses,
          capillary refill time - <em>May be expedited or skipped if time is
            very limited &amp; history suggests no UL issue.</em> (<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=p4GHGCM_aiM&amp;t=39s"

            class="timestamp">0:39</a>, <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=p4GHGCM_aiM&amp;t=508s"

            class="timestamp">8:28</a>)</li>
        <li><strong>Neurological Examination (Upper Limb):</strong>
          <ul>
            <li><em>Rationale for skipping/focusing: History questions about
                numbness/tingling and power were negative. Examiner might state
                findings are normal to save time.</em> (<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=p4GHGCM_aiM&amp;t=516s"

                class="timestamp">8:36</a>, <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=p4GHGCM_aiM&amp;t=501s"

                class="timestamp">8:21</a>)</li>
            <li>If proceeding:
              <ul>
                <li>Sensory: Fine touch, pain, vibration, proprioception (joint
                  position sense). (<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=p4GHGCM_aiM&amp;t=58s"

                    class="timestamp">0:58</a>)</li>
                <li>Motor: Bulk, Tone, Power (shoulder, elbow, wrist, fingers),
                  Reflexes. (<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=p4GHGCM_aiM&amp;t=66s"

                    class="timestamp">1:06</a>)</li>
              </ul>
            </li>
            <li><em>Likely finding if examiner prompts: "Upper limb examination
                is normal."</em> (<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=p4GHGCM_aiM&amp;t=509s"

                class="timestamp">8:29</a>)</li>
          </ul>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </li>

    <h4>II. EXAMINATION (Neck &amp; Upper Limb)</h4>

    <div class="video-container"> <iframe src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/sEhVgHRObQ4" title="Upper limb exam by Dr Ankur #GotAspirEd" allow="accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture; web-share" referrerpolicy="strict-origin-when-cross-origin" allowfullscreen="" height="864" frameborder="0" width="1520"> </iframe> </div>

    <p><em>Preparation: Cotton wool, neuropin, reflex hammer, 128Hz tuning fork
        (though sensory/reflexes may be expedited based on history).</em> (<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=p4GHGCM_aiM&amp;t=26s" class="timestamp">0:26</a>)</p>

    <h3>UPPER LIMB EXAMINATION (Whiplash/Brachial Plexus Context)</h3>

    <h4>INSPECTION</h4>

    <table style="width:100%; border-collapse: collapse;" border="1">
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Area / Aspect</th>
          <th>Observation Points (Video Time)</th>
          <th>Finding Left</th>
          <th>Finding Right</th>
          <th>Notes</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td>General Upper Limbs (Anterior/Posterior)</td>
          <td>Redness, swelling, sign of injury, scar mark of previous surgery,
            deformity, muscle wasting, muscle bulk. (<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=sEhVgHRObQ4&amp;t=233s" class="timestamp">3:53</a> - <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=sEhVgHRObQ4&amp;t=248s" class="timestamp">4:08</a>) </td>
          <td><br>
          </td>
          <td><br>
          </td>
          <td>Video states patient's muscle bulk "used to be normal" and "no
            deformity, no scar mark".</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <h4>PALPATION (Specifically for Tone in the video context for Upper Limbs)</h4>

    <p><em>Note: The video primarily demonstrates tone assessment for the upper
        limbs under "palpation." Tenderness palpation was shown for the neck.</em></p>

    <table style="width:100%; border-collapse: collapse;" border="1">
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Test</th>
          <th>Finding Left</th>
          <th>Finding Right</th>
          <th>Notes (Video Time)</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Tone</strong> (Assessed by passive movement at elbow and
            wrist)</td>
          <td><br>
          </td>
          <td><br>
          </td>
          <td>Patient asked to relax. Examiner performs passive
            flexion/extension at elbow and wrist. (<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=sEhVgHRObQ4&amp;t=250s" class="timestamp">4:10</a> - <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=sEhVgHRObQ4&amp;t=275s" class="timestamp">4:35</a>) </td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <h4>NEUROLOGICAL EXAMINATION</h4>

    <h3>Sensory System:</h3>

    <p><em>Modalities: Fine Touch (Cotton Wool), Pain Touch (Neuro Pin/Sharp
        object).</em></p>

    <p><em>Key: N = Normal (Intact), R = Reduced, A = Absent. (Patient says
        "yes" when felt).</em></p>

