            - <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=sEhVgHRObQ4&amp;t=383s" class="timestamp">6:23</a> (Directly on triceps tendon)</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Brachioradialis (Supinator)</td>
          <td>C5, C6</td>
          <td><br>
          </td>
          <td><br>
          </td>
          <td><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=sEhVgHRObQ4&amp;t=385s" class="timestamp">6:25</a>
            - <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=sEhVgHRObQ4&amp;t=395s" class="timestamp">6:35</a> (Tap over styloid process of radius /
            distal brachioradialis tendon)</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <p><em>(End of Upper Limb Neurological Examination as shown in video for
        Whiplash/Brachial Plexus context)</em></p>


        <h3>NECK EXAMINATION (Whiplash Context)</h3>

        <h4>INSPECTION</h4>
        <table style="width:100%; border-collapse: collapse;" border="1">
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Area / Aspect</th>
              <th>Observation Points (Video Time)</th>
              <th>Findings</th>
              <th>Notes</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td>General Neck (Anterior/Posterior/Lateral)</td>
              <td>Redness, swelling, sign of any injury, scar mark of previous surgery, deformity.
                (<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=sEhVgHRObQ4&t=40s" class="timestamp">0:40</a> - <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=sEhVgHRObQ4&t=49s" class="timestamp">0:49</a>)
              </td>
              <td></td>
              <td>Video states for the patient: "no redness, no swelling, no sign of any injury, no scar mark of the previous surgery or deformity."</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
        
        <h4>PALPATION</h4>
        <table style="width:100%; border-collapse: collapse;" border="1">
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Test</th>
              <th>Technique / Area Palpated (Video Time)</th>
              <th>Finding (Tenderness Present/Absent)</th>
              <th>Notes</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td>Spinal Tenderness (Spinous Processes)</td>
              <td>Palpation down the spinous processes.
                (<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=sEhVgHRObQ4&t=62s" class="timestamp">1:02</a> - <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=sEhVgHRObQ4&t=75s" class="timestamp">1:15</a>)
              </td>
              <td></td>
              <td>Patient to report any pain.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Paraspinal Tenderness</td>
              <td>Palpation of paraspinal muscles, can be done in a zigzag manner, one side at a time.
                (<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=sEhVgHRObQ4&t=75s" class="timestamp">1:15</a> - <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=sEhVgHRObQ4&t=93s" class="timestamp">1:33</a>)
              </td>
              <td></td>
              <td>Video notes patient showed tenderness in the right paraspinal area. (Example: "Tenderness noted right paraspinal C3-C5")</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
        
        <h4>RANGE OF MOTION (NECK MOVEMENTS)</h4>
        <p><em><b>Important Prerequisite:</b> Before proceeding with neck movements, ensure the neck is stabilized if any suspicion of instability. Cervical spine X-rays should be confirmed as normal if trauma is involved or there are red flags.
          (<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=sEhVgHRObQ4&t=402s" class="timestamp">6:42</a> - <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=sEhVgHRObQ4&t=414s" class="timestamp">6:54</a>)
        </em></p>
        <table style="width:100%; border-collapse: collapse;" border="1">
